Expectations — declarative data quality.

Expectations are predicates you attach to a dataset. When a row arrives that violates the predicate, the pipeline does one of three things, depending on which keyword you used.

With plain expect, the row is kept, but the violation is logged to the event log. With expect-or-drop, the violating row is dropped, and the violation is logged. With expect-or-fail, the pipeline fails on the very first violation.

So those are three escalating severities. Expect is for monitoring — you want to measure quality without changing the data. Expect-or-drop is for filtering — quarantine the bad rows but keep the pipeline flowing. And expect-or-fail is for critical rules where a single bad row means something is seriously wrong and the run must stop.

You can attach several expectations at once, mixing severities — for instance, log a missing customer id, drop an unreasonably large amount, and fail outright on an invalid currency. The whole point is that data quality becomes declarative metadata on the dataset, not hand-written validation code.
